		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Getting Started as a Barbarian Shaman(lvl 1 - 14)</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:comm_untouchables@hotmail.com">Draken</a> | 
		            2/24/2004 12:33:33 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">This guide is intended for anyone wanting to enjoy the game, as a Barbarian, as well as making money and leveling quickly from it.  I noticed a few guides describing, in some to no detail, how to play a Barbarian Shaman, or how to level quickly, but none on actually enjoying it.  This guide is also meant to take you up to the point that you can use Root and Bind, or Level 14.<br />
First, to start, always dump all extra points into Wisdom.  Helps a lot.  I know everyone will say, don't.  Dump into agi or dex or str, but there is no reason to do that.  Once you start getting spells, you start to self buff and see those points anyways.  You need gains and mana, so go the route of throwing all extra points into WIS.<br />
When you start, go see your guildmaster.  Give him your note, and put on your shirt...and get ready to fight.  Also, put a point into a few skills, namely 1H Blunt.  Do not throw anything into tradeskills like Smithing, nor Tailoring yet.<br />
You are going to be starting in Everfrost.  It is not a fun place, but it has the best newbie training area(levels 1 - 5) in Norrath.  However, you will have one small problem:trains.  Now, I wouldn't be too worried, but I would be ready to be prepared for them.  Also, please note, as far as creatures 'trained' onto you, usually, when there is a new expansion, no matter the server(as long as it is a non-PvP), the newbie area of Everfrost is very easy.  Usually, there is a guild, or a player, that will go through and Root or freeze all of the creatures that come by.  When there isn't a new expansion, it can be 'fun' for a new player:).<br />
Run out of Halas, through the tunnel and into Everfrost.  Equip your club and prepare to fight.  You want to take on any Decaying Skeletons and Goblins that 'con' above green to you, but below black/grey.  Simply right-click to do this, or left-click and then hit the 'C' key(this is a default keyboard setting.  You can also change this by clicking on your options button at the top of your screen).<br />
After you have gained a few levels, and have been selling back your wears to the vendor there, go into halas and buy some level one spells.  Get the following in this order:<br />
<div style="margin-left:20px;">Inner Fire<br />Burst of Flame<br />Strengthen<br />Dexterous Aura<br />Minor Healing<br />Cure Disease<br /></div><br />
Some of the spells are not essential, but you will probably find yourself using them to raise skills for later spells.<br />
Now, go back into Everfrost, and bash more, remembering to save the following if possible:<br /><div style="margin-left:20px">Goblin Necklaces<br />Spider Fungus<br />All Polar Bear Skins(ruined, low, med, high quality and white.<br />
</div><br />
The Goblin Neckalces can be turned in to Lysbith in the fighting pit in Halas.  Ask her 'how do I protect the pass?' and she will give you the bag.  Put in six necklaces, singly stacked, and she will give some coin, and exp, and ration/torch/something.<br />
The fungus can be turned in to Waltor Felligan.  Go to him and say 'I will assist in gathering fungus.'.  He will give a back.  Fill it, with single spider fungus from your spiderling friends, and combine.  Then return it to him.  He will give a spell and some coin.<br />
The regular polar bear skins(ruined, low, med and high quality) are either needed early, or will be used often later in your shaman life.  With the ruined, you can basically make your own armor.  Keep picking up spiderling silk and combining these until you have cords.  Make sure you have a sewing kit and have put at least one point of training into tailoring.  You will gain skill and have a lot of cord.  Do not sell though, just put each stack of 20 into your bank.  Or in a bag(from the goblins).  You can then raise your tailoring higher with the ruined bear skins(recipes at eqtraders.com).<br />
BUT!!!, the biggies for the skins are low, med and high quality, and the white bear skins.  Okay, so, the low and medium will be sold to players, kept for you to raise skill, or sold to NPC vendors--this is up to you.  But, the white and High Quality bear skins are what you are after.  In this quest database look up the new shaman newbie armor quests.  The white bear skins are essential in a few of these. You also need ore, and it is sold by the NPC vendor in Halas.  Get the armor, it looks good, and you will be wearing it for a lot of skill and level raising because it adds WIS, HP ANNNDDD AC in really good doses for early level players.  Now, after you have your newbie armor, you can turn in the white bear pelts to Lindl in Halas for some leather armor and XP.  Then, resell the armor for loot:)<br />
The high quality bear skins will make you feel rich early.  These are used by higher level tailorers(usually 88+) to make bags.  These are 10 slot, with weight reduction.  So, players buy these for 20+ Plat per skin, depending on server and the players available at the time.  I kept killing green-conning polar bear cubs while running to the tundra to kill calfes even after level 16, because it was basically free plat when you landed one.<br />
Anyhow, that is what you should be on the lookout for while beating things up.  I would also keep an eye out for decaying skeletons carrying a 2H Blunt weapon and a rapier, or some other decent-damaging piercing weapon higher than a knife/dagger.  With the way weapons are, you don't have to raise 1H blunt, 2H blunt <em>AND</em> piercing, but, there are some pretty cool weapons in the game that fall into that for a Barb Shaman, not to mention, your epic is a piercing weapon...so there ya go:).<br />
After you hit level 5, get back to Halas and buy more spells.  But, maybe you don't need to.  I know that with the Fungus quest, there are a lot of level 5 spells given.  So, you might actually have them all.  If not, be sure you have the following, in this order of need:<br/><div style="margin-left:20px;">Gate<br />Drowsy<br />Frost Rift<br />Feet Like Cat<br />Sicken<br />Summon Drink--only because you never have to buy water now:)<br />
</div>
Now, you start to have problems finding fights in the newbie area.  This is time that I recommend going to the Blackburrow Ramp in Everfrost and starting to fight Gnolls.  Buff up, stand away and cast poison on one.  Then run away and get ready to fight.  The idea of casting Poison is that it is a DoT(damage-over-time) spell.  It hits for some damage, then deals a few per click of combat.  Keep switching weapons as you fight(if you choose this way), and keep killing gnolls at the entrance a little around the bend and down the path.<br />
Aroudn this time, you can also go into Blackburrow, but be mindful, as this area holds a LOT of training of the monsters.  There are gnolls everywhere, from basic to harder, and sometimes there are plague creatures(rats, bears, etc) that travel here as well.  Do not go into any doors as of yet, but keep killing gnolls.  Save their armor, and their teeth.  Also, be sure to have your sewing kit with you and save their pelts.  You can make a cloak out of these by combining four pelts, with four, with four(or 64).  This cloak can be worn, or turned in to the Rogue guild for some XP, and more.  The teeth will be turned into the Guards of Qeynos for XP(read the quest for gnoll teeth -- it explains it all).  The teeth will, eventually, allow you to shop pretty freely in Qeynos, and, will give a decent amount of experience, even after level 14(not decent then, but still giving XP!).<br />
At level 9, go back to Halas and buy more spells.  You should not be doing the fungus, nor goblin necklace quests as of now.  These are now wastes of time to a level 9.  Now, you will get a magic hammer, and heading to Qeynos Hills for some willowisp bashing, if you choose.  There are also a lot of other places to go, namely hte Tundra in Everfrost for Orc Wristbands to be turned into Cindl again for Patchwork armor this time(sometimes receiving 1pp per piece).<br />
Buying your spells, you will need to make a small run to get a new DoT, Tainted Breath.  This is in a small area outside of guards where there is a single vendor selling DoTs.  Go off the halas ramp to your left.  Follow the newbie are down.  Turn right, then, at the fork, turn left instead of the right that I'm sure you always go.  Follow this down until you go past snowflake and some guards.  Hug the wall on your left until you pass three npcs.  Now, you should keep heading east and you see some ruins.  Look up on the ledge and you will see the NPC.  The only real threats I have ever seen on these trips are goblin scouts(should con green to a level 9), and skeletons(should still give XP, but are easy for you).<br />
But, back to Halas, and buy these spells, in the order as needed:<br />
<div style="margin-left:20px;">Spirit of Wolf<br />Light Healing<br />Spirit of Bear<br />Summon Food-Now, no more buying it!:)<br /></div>
Buy now, I had well over 200pp in the bank, along with a few pretty decent pieces of weaponry and armor.  All this for a week and half of casual play, and actually enjoying the game.  And I know what any argument might be, 'well I enjoy playing 8 hours a day and grouping and popwerleveling'.  YES, but I see those guides everywhere.:)<br />
Now, with Tainted Breath, Frost Rift, Light Healing and Spirit of Wolf, along with your buffs, I say fight in the tundra, and get spider silks and orc wristbands.  Also, you could 'try' to fight a mammoth calf, which would drain all of your juice:)  Or, keep fighting in Blackburrow.  Or, fight here, blackburrow and Qyenos Hill...now, it's really up to you.  Just, be sure to be ready for what you fight.  Yellows usually mean casting Tainted breath and running for a few ticks.  Then, recasting and running, then fighting.  It might sound time consuming, but you don't risk death.  This had me fighting mammoth calfs at level 9 and actually killing them with my 1h blunt.  Or, fight for more teeth in Blackburrow.  Make sure you do not go too deep into blackburrow, though.  Some gnolls can really hurt, and having eight on top of you can kill you fast.  Or, go to Qeynos hills and kill rabid animals, and big, bad bats.  If you did the quest to get the Tribunal summoning hammer, fight some willowisps along the way too, and should be able to enjoy some new fighting techniques, along with a very nice pace.<br />
The other point is that you can start using a tradeskill now.  For tailoring, everfrost is 100% the spot.  You get silks, hides and the like there.  Really, it's a nice spot.  Smithing can also be done here, as long as you can get your hands on a file.  Brewing, baking and the like can be handled pretty well in either halas(not recommended), or in Qeynos...once again, your choice.<br />
You will also find yourself raise up a little slowly to levels 13 and 14.  If this is the case, and you really want to, I say fight mammoth calfs(for their hides.  The hides(you need four) get turned in to the rogue guild for a really nice piece of armor that you can resell for some pp), fight willowisps(there is an island that you can take the ship to from Qeynos South, or fight deeper into blackburrow and get more teeth to turn in(watch doing this too much as sometimes the bad guards will con too hard on you and attack without provocation).<br />
Once you hit levels 14+, you can now get two spells which are what Spirit of Wolf was at level nine, Root and Bind.  Root holds a creature in place, which means your DoTs do more damage, or you have more time to med, and Bind let's you change your starting location/bind location to any other, as long as it is a 'city-type' location.  So, no more dieing on Kerra Isle(the island in Erud's Crossing), only to end up in Everfrost at the ramp.:)<br />
Thanks for reading and I hope you got something out of this guide, and can enjoy everquest on the same level that I do.

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
